Hokkien and Straits Chinese (Nonya) popiah are the main versions.

english: eat in at a restaurant To eat in at a restaurant. The antonym is "take away" or "tah-bao". Used by eatery or restaurant staff as in
meaning: "Having here or take away?" (Are you eating in here or do you want to have it for take-away?)

a remark (Often offensive) made against someone who is not of a legally minimum age allowed by the law. Or expression used to excuse someone because he is either immature or still too young to know the difference.
Abbreviated form of "is it?" used as a standard tag question. E.g.: You going home now issit? E.g.: You not going home issit? E.g.: Someone comments: "You look good today." Answer: "Issit??"

english: policies are out-dated A retort made against a person who refers to how policies were made in the past
meaning: or in response to something which is passe. Direct reference to the three-quarter khaki pants standard in Singapore police uniforms until 1969.

meaning: Military expression used during organisational foul-ups. Generally used as a response to "I thought..." or "I think..." when something goes wrong.
